[2] United Kingdom (England)
Date: Thu 8 Feb 2007
From: Pablo Nart <pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: BBC news [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6344335.stm>

The bird flu outbreak at a farm in Suffolk may be linked to imports
from the firm's plant in Hungary, the government has said. The
pathogenic H5N1 strain was found on a Hungarian geese farm in January
2007. Deputy Chief Vet Fred Landeg said a possible route of infection
was from imported "poultry products."
The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs said
preliminary scientific tests showed the 2 viruses "may well be
identical. Defra, the Food Standards Agency and the Health Protection
Agency are investigating the possibility of a link between the
Hungarian outbreaks, poultry meat from Hungary and the introduction
of disease in the farm in Suffolk," it added.
The company also has a division in Sarvar, Hungary. Defra said [the
farm company] was temporarily suspending the movement of poultry
products between the 2 outlets until the investigation is complete.
In a statement, [the farm company] said it continues to work closely
with Defra in its investigation. "We are cooperating fully, and, as a
precautionary measure, we have volunteered to cease any movements to
and from Hungary," it said. "We want to reassure consumers that [our]
products are perfectly safe to eat."
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo.nart@terra.es>
[The most recent Defra news release on this outbreak is:
