[4] United Kingdom (England)
Date: Mon 5 Feb 2007
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>

The fact that animal industry workers in Hungary, Romania and several
other Eastern European countries with endemic livestock disease
issues (notably CSF and now probably bird flu) are now free to move
around as migrant workers in the EC livestock and poultry industries
is a new dynamic that the EU as well as the UK needs to confront.
Based on what I remember from a presentation at the Avian Flu
symposium in Cambridge last April [2006], a model developed from H7N7
outbreaks in the Netherlands would predict that the date of the
actual initial index infection case in this outbreak should have been
about 10-14 days prior to the onset of this observable non-background
mortality (if it started from a single case).
Noticeable and exponential mortality increases in this model
developed at between 2 weeks to 3 weeks after initial disease
infection, as I recall. 1st infection takes 2 days to present, this
case infects 2 [cases] 2 days later, these 2 each infect 2 more etc.
Truly unmistakable catastrophic mortality kicks in at just about 2
weeks after infection of the index case in the flock.
The paper should be published in the symposium proceedings in an
upcoming Avian Diseases issue.
--
Joe Dudley
Chief Scientist, Biosecurity & Biosurveillance
EAI Corporation
<jdudley@eaicorp.com>
[If the Guardian/Observer is correct about the arrival of the partly
processed Hungarian turkeys on 27 Jan 2007 at the nearby processing
plant, this would possibly rule out that shipment as the probable
cause, as Movement Restrictions were imposed on 1 Feb 2007. But if
there was one shipment from Hungary, there could well have been
earlier ones in January 2007. To get from the processing plant to a
turkey house is another obstacle, but one should never rule out dirty boots.
Other questions arise: Has Defra implemented appropriate
surveillance, especially given that the government vets were unable
to identify this disease on clinical inspection? Was the
"contaminated food" distributed to any other sites? What route did
the lorry (or lorries?) take, and have other locations and countries
been alerted? Is withholding this information (or failing to alert a
suspicion on an un-named premises) because Defra considered it
"commercially confidential" consistent with their duty of care to
livestock, livestock keepers and the general public? - Mod.MHJ]
