[5] United Kingdom (England)
Date: 8 Feb 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: International Herald Tribune [edited]
<http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/02/08/europe/EU-GEN-Britain-Bird-Flu.php>

Transfer of turkeys from Hungary examined in British bird flu outbreak inquiry
-------------------------------------------
Scientists are investigating whether a bird flu outbreak at a British
poultry farm was caused by a consignment of dead turkeys imported
from Hungary, government officials said Thursday [8 Feb 2007]. The
Department of Environment, Food and Rural Affairs said it is
examining the transfer of partly processed birds from a Hungarian
plant to a farm in Holton, about 130 miles (210 km) northeast of
London, owned by [a company that is] Europe's biggest turkey producer.
A department spokeswoman said the 2 plants were linked but could not
confirm whether the Hungarian facility was owned by [the same farm
company involved in the Suffolk outbreak]. "Around 38 tons of partly
processed turkeys are transported from a linked Hungarian plant to
the Suffolk farm each week," said the spokeswoman, on customary
condition of anonymity in line with policy. "Investigations have
ruled out the transfer of the HN51 virus by workers traveling between
Hungary and Britain." The spokeswoman said the company had agreed to
temporarily suspend imports from Hungary.
She said that signs of H5N1 had been found in birds housed in 3 other
turkey sheds at the Holton farm, following the initial discovery of
the virus. "Results so far have confirmed the presence of the virus
in 4 out of 22 turkey sheds," the spokeswoman said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Considering the amount of foot-traffic on any poultry farm, this
finding that other houses contained infected birds is to be expected.
This reaffirms the wisdom of total culling when faced with this
virus. - Mod.MHJ]
