[These 2 OIE reports contain a couple of interesting pieces of
information. In the Pakistan outbreak, there are an unusually wide
variety of bird species involved, including parakeets, and it would
be beneficial to have more information on the relative distribution
of species, attack rate by species etc. on the outbreak farm at Lohar
Banda. Of course, some of these birds might have higher commercial
value than typical backyard poultry and may therefore be associated
with more movement off the farm before the outbreak but, hopefully,
not after the outbreak was in full swing.
The statistics given on the UK outbreak are a little disquieting
because they mean that all the birds in the affected house were
culled but that 95 percent of the birds on the farm complex remained.
However, this must be a reporting artifact, as today's report
indicates all 159 000 birds have now been culled. See Avian influenza
(27): UK (England) 20070207.0477. - Mod.PC]
